<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-08-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-08-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1386" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1386">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 419.11D29/45.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 498.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-08-11">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 11, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the disturbances which
                            took place in the city of Panama on July 4, 1912, I have the honor to
                            inform you that I have been informed by Señor Lefevre, the Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs, that the Panaman Government has already arrested seven
                                <pb facs="1183" n="1079" xml:id="pg_1079"/> officers of the police
                            force who are believed to have been concerned in the riot, and is
                            pursuing an investigation, a report upon which has been promised to me
                            within a very short time.</p>
                        <p>In view of the noticeable delay on the part of the Panaman Government in
                            pursuing this matter I have vigorously urged with Señor Lefevre that it
                            be given immediate attention and that the report be prepared as quickly
                            as possible setting forth the attitude and proposed action of the
                            Panaman Government in adjusting this affair along the lines indicated by
                            the Department.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cyrus F. Wicker</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>